Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: International Breweries, Eveready

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-20T15:51:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-20/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-international-breweries-eveready.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell 0.5
percent to 75.39 at the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi, the lowest
level since April 29.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index advanced for
the first day in four, climbing 0.3 percent to 25,790.64 by the
2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a statement on the
bourse’s website. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  dropped
0.5 percent to 845.36 by the 4 p.m. end of trading in  Windhoek .
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index snapped three days of losses, gaining
0.2 percent to 2,098.48 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index declined less than 0.1
percent to 1,178.13 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.        Eveready East Africa Ltd. (EVRD)  , a Kenyan dry-cell
battery maker, gained 10 cents, or 4.6 percent, to 2.3
shillings, the strongest closing level since April 19, after the
company appointed Jackson Mutua as its managing director.  International Breweries Plc (INTBREW)  , a Nigerian
brewer, lost 30 kobo, or 4.4 percent, to 6.5 naira, the weakest
close since May 12, after reporting a 98 percent drop in profit
to 7.4 million naira ($47,000) in the first quarter through
March.  Sasini Ltd. (STCL)  , a Kenyan tea and coffee producer,
climbed 0.55 shilling, or 5.3 percent, to 10.90 shillings, the
highest level since March 1 after the Nairobi-based Business
Daily newspaper reported the company’s half-year earnings will
boosted by lower financing costs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
